-- Lesson 1: Facebook Ad Policies & Common Violations
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="lesson-content"><h2>Facebook Ad Policies & Common Violations</h2><h3>Staying Compliant and Avoiding Disapprovals</h3><p>Facebook ad policies protect users and maintain platform quality. Understanding and following these policies prevents disapprovals and account restrictions. This lesson covers key policies and common violations to help you advertise successfully within guidelines.</p><h3>Why Ad Policies Matter</h3><p>Protect user experience. Maintain platform trust. Legal compliance requirements. Prevent fraud and scams. Quality control. Violations lead to disapprovals. Repeated violations risk account suspension. Compliance essential for sustainable advertising.</p><h3>Prohibited Content Categories</h3><p>Illegal products and services. Tobacco and drugs. Weapons and ammunition. Adult content and services. Misleading or false claims. Discriminatory practices. Sensational content. Absolute prohibitions, no exceptions.</p><h3>Restricted Content</h3><p>Alcohol (age and location restrictions). Dating services (compliance required). Online gambling (licensed only). Financial services (disclosure requirements). Healthcare products (approval needed). Political ads (authorization required). Know restrictions for your industry.</p><h3>Image and Video Requirements</h3><p>No excessive text in images (20% rule relaxed but still relevant). No shocking or sensational imagery. Accurate product representation. No before/after health claims. Quality standards. Appropriate for all audiences. Visual compliance critical.</p><h3>Landing Page Requirements</h3><p>Functional landing page required. Relevant to ad content. Clear business information. Privacy policy accessible. Secure checkout for e-commerce. No misleading redirects. Landing page quality affects approval.</p><h3>Targeting Restrictions</h3><p>No discriminatory targeting for housing, employment, credit. Age restrictions for certain categories. Location requirements for some products. Ethical targeting practices. Compliance with anti-discrimination laws. Targeting policies strictly enforced.</p><h3>Common Violation Examples</h3><p>Exaggerated claims ("Lose 50 pounds in 1 week"). Before/after images for health products. Targeting based on sensitive attributes. Misleading pricing or availability. Clickbait headlines. Sensational imagery. Learn from common mistakes.</p><h3>Special Ad Categories</h3><p>Housing, employment, credit have special rules. Limited targeting options. Certification required. Strict compliance monitoring. Understand requirements before advertising. Violations have serious consequences.</p><h3>Political and Social Issues Ads</h3><p>Authorization required. "Paid for by" disclaimer. Ad library transparency. Spending limits. Restricted targeting. Compliance verification. Special category with unique requirements.</p><h3>Trademark and Copyright</h3><p>Respect intellectual property. Do not use others trademarks without permission. Original or licensed content only. Avoid copyright infringement. Legal consequences for violations. Protect your own and respect others rights.</p><h3>Data Use and Privacy</h3><p>Comply with privacy regulations. Transparent data practices. Proper consent for data collection. Secure data handling. Privacy policy required. GDPR, CCPA compliance. Privacy violations serious.</p><h3>Review Process</h3><p>Automated review initially. Human review if flagged. Typically 24 hours or less. Can request manual review. Appeals process available. Understand review system. Patience during review period.</p><h3>Preventing Disapprovals</h3><p>Review policies before creating ads. Conservative approach to borderline content. Test ads with small budgets first. Quality over sensationalism. Accurate representations. Professional creative. Proactive compliance prevents issues.</p><h3>Handling Disapprovals</h3><p>Review disapproval reason carefully. Edit ad to address issue. Request review if believe error. Do not repeatedly submit same violation. Learn from feedback. Systematic approach to resolution.</p><h3>Account Quality and Trust</h3><p>Compliance history affects account standing. Repeated violations increase restrictions. Good standing enables more features. Build trust through compliance. Long-term perspective important. Protect account health.</p><h3>Staying Updated</h3><p>Policies change regularly. Monitor policy updates. Subscribe to Facebook Business updates. Join advertiser communities. Continuous learning required. Ignorance not excuse for violations.</p><h3>Key Takeaways</h3><ul><li>Facebook ad policies protect users and maintain quality</li><li>Prohibited content includes illegal products, adult content, misleading claims</li><li>Restricted categories have special requirements</li><li>Image, video, and landing page standards must be met</li><li>Special categories (housing, employment, credit, political) have strict rules</li><li>Respect intellectual property and privacy regulations</li><li>Proactive compliance prevents disapprovals</li><li>Stay updated on policy changes regularly</li></ul><p>Next lesson covers Getting Unbanned & Appeal Process.</p></div>'
WHERE title = 'Facebook Ad Policies & Common Violations' AND EXISTS (
    SELECT 1 FROM modules m JOIN courses c ON m.course_id = c.id 
    WHERE m.id = lessons.module_id AND c.title LIKE '%Facebook%Ads%Mastery%'
);

-- Lesson 2: Getting Unbanned & Appeal Process
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="lesson-content"><h2>Getting Unbanned & Appeal Process</h2><h3>Recovering from Account Restrictions</h3><p>Account restrictions and bans can happen even to compliant advertisers. Understanding the appeal process and prevention strategies helps recover access and prevent future issues. This lesson guides you through restrictions, appeals, and account protection.</p><h3>Types of Restrictions</h3><p>Ad disapproval: single ad rejected. Ad account restriction: limited functionality. Ad account disabled: cannot advertise. Business Manager restriction: broader impact. Page restrictions: content violations. Severity varies by violation type.</p><h3>Common Restriction Reasons</h3><p>Policy violations. Payment issues. Suspicious activity. Rapid account changes. Low-quality ads. User feedback. Automated system flags. Understanding causes helps prevention.</p><h3>Immediate Steps After Restriction</h3><p>Do not panic or act hastily. Review restriction notification carefully. Identify specific violation if stated. Check Account Quality in Business Manager. Gather relevant information. Prepare appeal systematically. Calm, methodical approach best.</p><h3>Account Quality Score</h3><p>Found in Business Manager settings. Shows account health status. Policy violations impact score. User feedback affects rating. Low quality increases restriction risk. Monitor regularly. Maintain good standing proactively.</p><h3>Appeal Process Overview</h3><p>Submit appeal through proper channels. Provide clear, concise explanation. Include relevant evidence. Professional, respectful tone. Acknowledge mistakes if applicable. Request specific resolution. Follow up appropriately.</p><h3>Writing Effective Appeals</h3><p>State facts clearly. Explain circumstances. Show understanding of policies. Describe corrective actions taken. Provide supporting documentation. Professional language. Concise but complete. Quality appeals get better results.</p><h3>What to Include in Appeal</h3><p>Account or ad ID. Specific issue being appealed. Timeline of events. Explanation of situation. Evidence supporting your case. Steps taken to prevent recurrence. Contact information. Comprehensive appeals processed faster.</p><h3>Appeal Channels</h3><p>In-platform appeal button. Business Support inbox. Facebook Business Help Center. Ads Manager support. Use official channels only. Avoid social media complaints. Proper channels get proper attention.</p><h3>Response Timeline</h3><p>Typically 24-48 hours. Can take longer for complex cases. No response after 7 days, follow up. Patience important. Multiple appeals may slow process. Wait for response before resubmitting.</p><h3>If Appeal Denied</h3><p>Review denial reason carefully. Address specific concerns. Submit new appeal with additional information. Consider alternative approaches. Escalate through proper channels if appropriate. Persistent but professional.</p><h3>Prevention Strategies</h3><p>Follow all policies strictly. Quality over quantity. Gradual account growth. Maintain payment methods. Respond to warnings promptly. Regular account audits. Proactive compliance. Prevention better than cure.</p><h3>Account Backup Plans</h3><p>Multiple Business Managers. Backup ad accounts. Diversify payment methods. Document account setup. Export data regularly. Contingency planning. Reduce single point of failure.</p><h3>Working with Facebook Support</h3><p>Professional communication. Provide requested information promptly. Follow instructions carefully. Document all interactions. Escalate appropriately if needed. Build positive relationship. Support can help or hurt.</p><h3>Learning from Restrictions</h3><p>Analyze what went wrong. Implement corrective measures. Update processes and training. Document lessons learned. Share knowledge with team. Continuous improvement. Turn setbacks into learning.</p><h3>Long-Term Account Health</h3><p>Consistent policy compliance. Quality ad creative. Positive user feedback. Stable payment history. Gradual, sustainable growth. Regular monitoring. Healthy accounts rarely restricted.</p><h3>When to Start Fresh</h3><p>Permanent ban with no appeal success. Severely damaged account reputation. Sometimes new start better. Follow proper procedures. Learn from past mistakes. Fresh start opportunity.</p><h3>Key Takeaways</h3><ul><li>Restrictions range from ad disapproval to account disable</li><li>Act calmly and systematically when restricted</li><li>Appeal through official channels with clear, professional communication</li><li>Include specific details and supporting evidence</li><li>Monitor Account Quality score proactively</li><li>Prevention through compliance better than appeals</li><li>Have backup plans and contingencies</li><li>Learn from restrictions to prevent recurrence</li></ul><p>Next lesson covers Ethical Advertising Practices.</p></div>'
WHERE title = 'Getting Unbanned & Appeal Process' AND EXISTS (
    SELECT 1 FROM modules m JOIN courses c ON m.course_id = c.id 
    WHERE m.id = lessons.module_id AND c.title LIKE '%Facebook%Ads%Mastery%'
);

-- Lesson 3: Ethical Advertising Practices
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="lesson-content"><h2>Ethical Advertising Practices</h2><h3>Building Trust Through Responsible Marketing</h3><p>Ethical advertising goes beyond compliance with policies. It builds long-term trust, protects brand reputation, and creates sustainable business success. This lesson explores ethical principles and practices that benefit advertisers, customers, and society.</p><h3>Why Ethics Matter in Advertising</h3><p>Build customer trust and loyalty. Protect brand reputation. Sustainable long-term success. Legal and regulatory compliance. Social responsibility. Competitive differentiation. Ethical practices good for business and society.</p><h3>Honesty and Transparency</h3><p>Truthful product claims. Accurate pricing information. Clear terms and conditions. Transparent business practices. No hidden fees or charges. Honest advertising builds trust. Deception destroys reputation.</p><h3>Respecting Privacy</h3><p>Transparent data collection. Proper consent mechanisms. Secure data handling. Minimal data collection. Clear privacy policies. Respect user preferences. Privacy-first approach sustainable.</p><h3>Avoiding Manipulation</h3><p>No dark patterns or tricks. Honest scarcity and urgency. Authentic social proof. Ethical persuasion techniques. Respect user autonomy. Manipulation short-term gain, long-term loss.</p><h3>Inclusive and Non-Discriminatory</h3><p>Diverse representation in creative. Accessible to all users. No discriminatory targeting. Inclusive messaging. Respectful of all groups. Diversity good for business and society.</p><h3>Protecting Vulnerable Populations</h3><p>Extra care with children. Responsible marketing to elderly. Sensitivity to vulnerable groups. Age-appropriate content. Ethical standards higher for at-risk populations.</p><h3>Environmental and Social Responsibility</h3><p>Truthful environmental claims. Avoid greenwashing. Support positive social causes. Responsible consumption messaging. Corporate social responsibility. Values-aligned marketing.</p><h3>Competitor Respect</h3><p>Fair competitive practices. No false comparisons. Respect intellectual property. Honest differentiation. Compete on value, not deception. Ethical competition benefits industry.</p><h3>Quality Over Clickbait</h3><p>Valuable content and offers. Accurate headlines. Deliver on promises. No misleading thumbnails. Quality builds audience. Clickbait damages trust.</p><h3>Responsible Retargeting</h3><p>Appropriate frequency caps. Respect user signals. Exclude when appropriate. No excessive following. Balance persistence with respect. Ethical retargeting maintains relationships.</p><h3>Transparent Influencer Partnerships</h3><p>Clear disclosure of partnerships. Authentic endorsements only. Honest product experiences. FTC compliance. Transparency builds credibility. Deceptive partnerships backfire.</p><h3>Accessibility Considerations</h3><p>Captions for videos. Alt text for images. Clear, readable fonts. Color contrast for visibility. Accessible landing pages. Inclusive design reaches more people.</p><h3>Cultural Sensitivity</h3><p>Respect cultural differences. Avoid stereotypes. Appropriate localization. Cultural awareness. Inclusive global marketing. Sensitivity prevents offense and builds connection.</p><h3>Ethical Decision Framework</h3><p>Would you be proud if this was public? Does it respect user autonomy? Is it honest and transparent? Does it create real value? Would you want this done to you? Ethical framework guides decisions.</p><h3>Building Ethical Culture</h3><p>Leadership commitment. Team training. Clear guidelines. Accountability systems. Reward ethical behavior. Continuous improvement. Culture drives consistent ethics.</p><h3>Long-Term Perspective</h3><p>Short-term gains vs long-term trust. Reputation takes years to build, moments to destroy. Ethical practices sustainable. Customer lifetime value over quick sales. Think long-term.</p><h3>Key Takeaways</h3><ul><li>Ethical advertising builds trust and sustainable success</li><li>Honesty and transparency fundamental principles</li><li>Respect privacy and user autonomy</li><li>Inclusive, non-discriminatory practices essential</li><li>Protect vulnerable populations with extra care</li><li>Quality content over manipulative clickbait</li><li>Cultural sensitivity and accessibility important</li><li>Ethical framework guides decision-making</li></ul><p>Next lesson covers Troubleshooting Disapproved Ads.</p></div>'
WHERE title = 'Ethical Advertising Practices' AND EXISTS (
    SELECT 1 FROM modules m JOIN courses c ON m.course_id = c.id 
    WHERE m.id = lessons.module_id AND c.title LIKE '%Facebook%Ads%Mastery%'
);
